data.content:
Yes! Two better options in MSTest:

**1. `[DataRow]` — simplest for inline constants:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**2. Strongly-typed `DynamicData` (MSTest 3.x+) — best when you need computed/complex data:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why these are better:**
- **`DataRow`** eliminates the property entirely — less boilerplate.
- **Typed tuples** give you compile-time type safety instead of `object[]`, catching mismatches at build time rather than runtime.

Use `DataRow` for simple literals; use typed `DynamicData` when test data is computed, shared, or too complex for attributes.
